metrics_conclusion: In terms of chords and melody, Whistle has complexity on par with the typical song, having near-average scores in Chord Complexity and Chord-Melody Tension and below-average scores in Melodic Complexity, Chord Progression Novelty and Chord-Bass Melody.
key_conclusion: Whistle has sections analyzed in the following keys: D♭ Major, E Major,  and C♯ Mixolydian.  Click on the linked cheat sheets for popular chords, chord progressions, downloadable midi files and more!

metadata.editComments: Changed key from C# mixolydian to C# phrygian dominant. Added D note to measures 4 and 8.

With the verse, we quickly learn we have traveled into standard C#/Db major when the melody touches on the major 6 (Bb), which was flattened in the intro. This adds an evolving sound to the track as it progresses, and this song shifts modes with just about every section, so get used to it haha. With the harmony still not present, the sparse bass outlines a C#5 chord, bouncing between C#, G# and the octave on syncopated beats.

...aaaaand we've modulated to E major, using the parallel minor of our previous section in its relative major mode! It's almost like we've borrowed this whole section from the minor, and the tension of the dominant G#7 helps to send us falling right back into the C# Mixolydian b6 for the post-chorus

Back to C# Mixolydian b6! Since the "whistled" melody is transcribed in the Intro, I outlined the basic notes from the vocalists on the Post-Chorus. Most of it is more spoken than sung, but then there's a quick harmonized 3 note tag that emphasizes the major quality of this mode despite its initial minor sound, this adds a really cool effect and leads nicely back into the next verse.

And we visit E major one last time to happy-it-up before the outro. This time the progression flips its order, actually using the dominant as a passing chord instead of just a transition, though we do have the same buildup and resolution that was in the chorus. The heavy stick on the nondiatonic note here with the use of long and accented beats really makes this melody hit hard and contrasts with the falsetto vocal run that guides the transition to the outro

The end of the track is a rhythmically intensified permutation of the turnaround. Lots more syncopated percussion along with the occasional horn stabs accompany the bass that's now going all out with it's 1-5-1 line, repeating every two beats now instead of every other measure, driving the track to it's abrupt end. Melody and harmony remain the same, though.
